<p>I was looking through the source code for the <code>imghdr</code> module, which is part of the python standard library (I use 2.7). The structure is pretty simpleâ€”a <code>what</code> function that iterates over a list of functions with names like <code>test_filetype</code>, and if the passed in file matches any of the tests, it returns the string for that filetype.</p>  <p>All of the <code>test_filetype</code> functions take two arguments, <code>h</code> and <code>f</code>. <code>h</code> is a string with the contents of <code>f.read(32)</code>, and <code>f</code> is the open file object. None of the <code>test_filetype</code> functions actually use <code>f</code> for anything.</p>  <p>Why would the set of <code>test_filetype</code> functions all take an argument that is never used? </p>